44/*
45 * We don't write DLT_* values to capture files, because they're not the
46 * same on all platforms.
47 *
48 * Unfortunately, the various flavors of BSD have not always used the same
49 * numerical values for the same data types, and various patches to
50 * libpcap for non-BSD OSes have added their own DLT_* codes for link
51 * layer encapsulation types seen on those OSes, and those codes have had,
52 * in some cases, values that were also used, on other platforms, for other
53 * link layer encapsulation types.
54 *
55 * This means that capture files of a type whose numerical DLT_* code
56 * means different things on different BSDs, or with different versions
57 * of libpcap, can't always be read on systems other than those like
58 * the one running on the machine on which the capture was made.
59 *
60 * Instead, we define here a set of LINKTYPE_* codes, and map DLT_* codes
61 * to LINKTYPE_* codes when writing a savefile header, and map LINKTYPE_*
62 * codes to DLT_* codes when reading a savefile header.
63 *
64 * For those DLT_* codes that have, as far as we know, the same values on
65 * all platforms (DLT_NULL through DLT_FDDI), we define LINKTYPE_xxx as
66 * DLT_xxx; that way, captures of those types can still be read by
67 * versions of libpcap that map LINKTYPE_* values to DLT_* values, and
68 * captures of those types written by versions of libpcap that map DLT_
69 * values to LINKTYPE_ values can still be read by older versions
70 * of libpcap.
71 *
72 * The other LINKTYPE_* codes are given values starting at 100, in the
73 * hopes that no DLT_* code will be given one of those values.
74 *
75 * In order to ensure that a given LINKTYPE_* code's value will refer to
76 * the same encapsulation type on all platforms, you should not allocate
77 * a new LINKTYPE_* value without consulting
78 * "tcpdump-workers@lists.tcpdump.org". The tcpdump developers will
79 * allocate a value for you, and will not subsequently allocate it to
80 * anybody else; that value will be added to the "pcap.h" in the
81 * tcpdump.org Git repository, so that a future libpcap release will
82 * include it.
83 *
84 * You should, if possible, also contribute patches to libpcap and tcpdump
85 * to handle the new encapsulation type, so that they can also be checked
86 * into the tcpdump.org Git repository and so that they will appear in
87 * future libpcap and tcpdump releases.
88 *
89 * Do *NOT* assume that any values after the largest value in this file
90 * are available; you might not have the most up-to-date version of this
91 * file, and new values after that one might have been assigned. Also,
92 * do *NOT* use any values below 100 - those might already have been
93 * taken by one (or more!) organizations.
94 *
95 * Any platform that defines additional DLT_* codes should:
96 *
97 * request a LINKTYPE_* code and value from tcpdump.org,
98 * as per the above;
99 *
100 * add, in their version of libpcap, an entry to map
101 * those DLT_* codes to the corresponding LINKTYPE_*
102 * code;
103 *
104 * redefine, in their "net/bpf.h", any DLT_* values
105 * that collide with the values used by their additional
106 * DLT_* codes, to remove those collisions (but without
107 * making them collide with any of the LINKTYPE_*
108 * values equal to 50 or above; they should also avoid
109 * defining DLT_* values that collide with those
110 * LINKTYPE_* values, either).
111 */
112#define LINKTYPE_NULL DLT_NULL
113#define LINKTYPE_ETHERNET DLT_EN10MB /* also for 100Mb and up */
114#define LINKTYPE_EXP_ETHERNET DLT_EN3MB /* 3Mb experimental Ethernet */
115#define LINKTYPE_AX25 DLT_AX25
116#define LINKTYPE_PRONET DLT_PRONET
117#define LINKTYPE_CHAOS DLT_CHAOS
118#define LINKTYPE_IEEE802_5 DLT_IEEE802 /* DLT_IEEE802 is used for 802.5 Token Ring */
119#define LINKTYPE_ARCNET_BSD DLT_ARCNET /* BSD-style headers */
120#define LINKTYPE_SLIP DLT_SLIP
121#define LINKTYPE_PPP DLT_PPP
122#define LINKTYPE_FDDI DLT_FDDI

124/*
125 * LINKTYPE_PPP is for use when there might, or might not, be an RFC 1662
126 * PPP in HDLC-like framing header (with 0xff 0x03 before the PPP protocol
127 * field) at the beginning of the packet.
128 *
129 * This is for use when there is always such a header; the address field
130 * might be 0xff, for regular PPP, or it might be an address field for Cisco
131 * point-to-point with HDLC framing as per section 4.3.1 of RFC 1547 ("Cisco
132 * HDLC"). This is, for example, what you get with NetBSD's DLT_PPP_SERIAL.
133 *
134 * We give it the same value as NetBSD's DLT_PPP_SERIAL, in the hopes that
135 * nobody else will choose a DLT_ value of 50, and so that DLT_PPP_SERIAL
136 * captures will be written out with a link type that NetBSD's tcpdump
137 * can read.
138 */
139#define LINKTYPE_PPP_HDLC 50 /* PPP in HDLC-like framing */
140
141#define LINKTYPE_PPP_ETHER 51 /* NetBSD PPP-over-Ethernet */
142
143#define LINKTYPE_SYMANTEC_FIREWALL 99 /* Symantec Enterprise Firewall */
144
145/*

156/*
157 * Values starting with 104 are used for newly-assigned link-layer
158 * header type values; for those link-layer header types, the DLT_
159 * value returned by pcap_datalink() and passed to pcap_open_dead(),
160 * and the LINKTYPE_ value that appears in capture files, are the
161 * same.
162 *
163 * LINKTYPE_MATCHING_MIN is the lowest such value; LINKTYPE_MATCHING_MAX
164 * is the highest such value.
165 */

258/*
259 * Reserved for private use. If you have some link-layer header type
260 * that you want to use within your organization, with the capture files
261 * using that link-layer header type not ever be sent outside your
262 * organization, you can use these values.
263 *
264 * No libpcap release will use these for any purpose, nor will any
265 * tcpdump release use them, either.
266 *
267 * Do *NOT* use these in capture files that you expect anybody not using
268 * your private versions of capture-file-reading tools to read; in
269 * particular, do *NOT* use them in products, otherwise you may find that
270 * people won't be able to use tcpdump, or snort, or Ethereal, or... to
271 * read capture files from your firewall/intrusion detection/traffic
272 * monitoring/etc. appliance, or whatever product uses that LINKTYPE_ value,
273 * and you may also find that the developers of those applications will
274 * not accept patches to let them read those files.
275 *
276 * Also, do not use them if somebody might send you a capture using them
277 * for *their* private type and tools using them for *your* private type
278 * would have to read them.
279 *
280 * Instead, in those cases, ask "tcpdump-workers@lists.tcpdump.org" for a
281 * new DLT_ and LINKTYPE_ value, as per the comment in pcap/bpf.h, and use
282 * the type you're given.
283 */

285#define LINKTYPE_USER1 148

323/*
324 * Another PPP variant as per request from Karsten Keil <kkeil@suse.de>.
325 *
326 * This is used in some OSes to allow a kernel socket filter to distinguish
327 * between incoming and outgoing packets, on a socket intended to
328 * supply pppd with outgoing packets so it can do dial-on-demand and
329 * hangup-on-lack-of-demand; incoming packets are filtered out so they
330 * don't cause pppd to hold the connection up (you don't want random
331 * input packets such as port scans, packets from old lost connections,
332 * etc. to force the connection to stay up).
333 *
334 * The first byte of the PPP header (0xff03) is modified to accomodate
335 * the direction - 0x00 = IN, 0x01 = OUT.
336 */
337#define LINKTYPE_PPP_PPPD 166

611/*
612 * IEEE 802.15.4, exactly as it appears in the spec (no padding, no
613 * nothing), but with the PHY-level data for non-ASK PHYs (4 octets
614 * of 0 as preamble, one octet of SFD, one octet of frame length+
615 * reserved bit, and then the MAC-layer data, starting with the
616 * frame control field).
617 *

697/*
698 * Solaris ipnet pseudo-header; requested by Darren Reed <Darren.Reed@Sun.COM>.
699 *
700 * The pseudo-header starts with a one-byte version number; for version 2,
701 * the pseudo-header is:
702 *
703 * struct dl_ipnetinfo {
704 * uint8_t dli_version;
705 * uint8_t dli_family;
706 * uint16_t dli_htype;
707 * uint32_t dli_pktlen;
708 * uint32_t dli_ifindex;
709 * uint32_t dli_grifindex;
710 * uint32_t dli_zsrc;
711 * uint32_t dli_zdst;
712 * };
713 *
714 * dli_version is 2 for the current version of the pseudo-header.
715 *
716 * dli_family is a Solaris address family value, so it's 2 for IPv4
717 * and 26 for IPv6.
718 *
719 * dli_htype is a "hook type" - 0 for incoming packets, 1 for outgoing
720 * packets, and 2 for packets arriving from another zone on the same
721 * machine.
722 *
723 * dli_pktlen is the length of the packet data following the pseudo-header
724 * (so the captured length minus dli_pktlen is the length of the
725 * pseudo-header, assuming the entire pseudo-header was captured).
726 *
727 * dli_ifindex is the interface index of the interface on which the
728 * packet arrived.
729 *
730 * dli_grifindex is the group interface index number (for IPMP interfaces).
731 *
732 * dli_zsrc is the zone identifier for the source of the packet.
733 *
734 * dli_zdst is the zone identifier for the destination of the packet.
735 *
736 * A zone number of 0 is the global zone; a zone number of 0xffffffff
737 * means that the packet arrived from another host on the network, not
738 * from another zone on the same machine.
739 *
740 * An IPv4 or IPv6 datagram follows the pseudo-header; dli_family indicates
741 * which of those it is.
742 */
743#define LINKTYPE_IPNET 226
744
745/*
746 * CAN (Controller Area Network) frames, with a pseudo-header as supplied

748 * in big-endian byte order.

1100static struct linktype_map {
1101 int dlt;
1102 int linktype;
1103} map[] = {
1104 /*
1105 * These DLT_* codes have LINKTYPE_* codes with values identical
1106 * to the values of the corresponding DLT_* code.
1107 */
1108 { DLT_NULL, LINKTYPE_NULL },
1109 { DLT_EN10MB, LINKTYPE_ETHERNET },
1110 { DLT_EN3MB, LINKTYPE_EXP_ETHERNET },
1111 { DLT_AX25, LINKTYPE_AX25 },
1112 { DLT_PRONET, LINKTYPE_PRONET },
1113 { DLT_CHAOS, LINKTYPE_CHAOS },
1114 { DLT_IEEE802, LINKTYPE_IEEE802_5 },
1115 { DLT_ARCNET, LINKTYPE_ARCNET_BSD },
1116 { DLT_SLIP, LINKTYPE_SLIP },
1117 { DLT_PPP, LINKTYPE_PPP },
1118 { DLT_FDDI, LINKTYPE_FDDI },
1119 { DLT_SYMANTEC_FIREWALL, LINKTYPE_SYMANTEC_FIREWALL },
1120
1121 /*
1122 * These DLT_* codes have different values on different
1123 * platforms; we map them to LINKTYPE_* codes that
1124 * have values that should never be equal to any DLT_*
1125 * code.
1126 */
1127#ifdef DLT_FR
1128 /* BSD/OS Frame Relay */
1129 { DLT_FR, LINKTYPE_FRELAY },
1130#endif
1131
1132 { DLT_ATM_RFC1483, LINKTYPE_ATM_RFC1483 },
1133 { DLT_RAW, LINKTYPE_RAW },
1134 { DLT_SLIP_BSDOS, LINKTYPE_SLIP_BSDOS },
1135 { DLT_PPP_BSDOS, LINKTYPE_PPP_BSDOS },
1136
1137 /* BSD/OS Cisco HDLC */
1138 { DLT_C_HDLC, LINKTYPE_C_HDLC },
1139
1140 /*
1141 * These DLT_* codes are not on all platforms, but, so far,
1142 * there don't appear to be any platforms that define
1143 * other codes with those values; we map them to
1144 * different LINKTYPE_* values anyway, just in case.
1145 */
1146
1147 /* Linux ATM Classical IP */
1148 { DLT_ATM_CLIP, LINKTYPE_ATM_CLIP },
1149
1150 /* NetBSD sync/async serial PPP (or Cisco HDLC) */
1151 { DLT_PPP_SERIAL, LINKTYPE_PPP_HDLC },
1152
1153 /* NetBSD PPP over Ethernet */
1154 { DLT_PPP_ETHER, LINKTYPE_PPP_ETHER },
1155
1156 /*
1157 * All LINKTYPE_ values between LINKTYPE_MATCHING_MIN
1158 * and LINKTYPE_MATCHING_MAX are mapped to identical
1159 * DLT_ values.
1160 */
1161
1162 { -1, -1 }
1163};
1164
1165int
1166dlt_to_linktype(int dlt)
1167{
1168 int i;
1169
1170 /*
1171 * DLTs that, on some platforms, have values in the matching range
1172 * but that *don't* have the same value as the corresponding
1173 * LINKTYPE because, for some reason, not all OSes have the
1174 * same value for that DLT (note that the DLT's value might be
1175 * outside the matching range on some of those OSes).
1176 */
1177 if (dlt == DLT_PFSYNC)
1178 return (LINKTYPE_PFSYNC);
1179 if (dlt == DLT_PKTAP)
1180 return (LINKTYPE_PKTAP);
1181
1182 /*
1183 * For all other values in the matching range, the DLT
1184 * value is the same as the LINKTYPE value.
1185 */
1186 if (dlt >= DLT_MATCHING_MIN && dlt <= DLT_MATCHING_MAX)
1187 return (dlt);
1188
1189 /*
1190 * Map the values outside that range.
1191 */
1192 for (i = 0; map[i].dlt != -1; i++) {
1193 if (map[i].dlt == dlt)
1194 return (map[i].linktype);
1195 }
1196
1197 /*
1198 * If we don't have a mapping for this DLT, return an
1199 * error; that means that this is a value with no corresponding
1200 * LINKTYPE, and we need to assign one.
1201 */
1202 return (-1);
1203}
1204
1205int
1206linktype_to_dlt(int linktype)
1207{
1208 int i;
1209
1210 /*
1211 * LINKTYPEs in the matching range that *don't*
1212 * have the same value as the corresponding DLTs
1213 * because, for some reason, not all OSes have the
1214 * same value for that DLT.
1215 */
1216 if (linktype == LINKTYPE_PFSYNC)
1217 return (DLT_PFSYNC);
1218 if (linktype == LINKTYPE_PKTAP)
1219 return (DLT_PKTAP);
1220
1221 /*
1222 * For all other values in the matching range, the LINKTYPE
1223 * value is the same as the DLT value.
1224 */
1225 if (linktype >= LINKTYPE_MATCHING_MIN &&
1226 linktype <= LINKTYPE_MATCHING_MAX)
1227 return (linktype);
1228
1229 /*
1230 * Map the values outside that range.
1231 */
1232 for (i = 0; map[i].linktype != -1; i++) {
1233 if (map[i].linktype == linktype)
1234 return (map[i].dlt);
1235 }
1236
1237 /*
1238 * If we don't have an entry for this LINKTYPE, return
1239 * the link type value; it may be a DLT from an older
1240 * version of libpcap.
1241 */
1242 return linktype;
1243}
1244
1245/*
1246 * Return the maximum snapshot length for a given DLT_ value.
1247 *
1248 * For most link-layer types, we use MAXIMUM_SNAPLEN, but for DLT_DBUS,
1249 * the maximum is 134217728, as per
1250 *
1251 * https://dbus.freedesktop.org/doc/dbus-specification.html#message-protocol-messages
1252 */
1253u_int
1254max_snaplen_for_dlt(int dlt)
1255{
1256 if (dlt == DLT_DBUS)
1257 return 134217728;
1258 else
1259 return MAXIMUM_SNAPLEN;
1260}
1261
1262/*
1263 * DLT_LINUX_SLL packets with a protocol type of LINUX_SLL_P_CAN or
1264 * LINUX_SLL_P_CANFD have SocketCAN headers in front of the payload,
1265 * with the CAN ID being in host byte order.
1266 *
1267 * When reading a DLT_LINUX_SLL capture file, we need to check for those
1268 * packets and convert the CAN ID from the byte order of the host that
1269 * wrote the file to this host's byte order.
1270 */
1271static void
1272swap_linux_sll_header(const struct pcap_pkthdr *hdr, u_char *buf)
1273{
1274 u_int caplen = hdr->caplen;
1275 u_int length = hdr->len;
1276 struct sll_header *shdr = (struct sll_header *)buf;
1277 uint16_t protocol;
1278 pcap_can_socketcan_hdr *chdr;
1279
1280 if (caplen < (u_int) sizeof(struct sll_header) ||
1281 length < (u_int) sizeof(struct sll_header)) {
1282 /* Not enough data to have the protocol field */
1283 return;
1284 }
1285
1286 protocol = EXTRACT_16BITS(&shdr->sll_protocol);
1287 if (protocol != LINUX_SLL_P_CAN && protocol != LINUX_SLL_P_CANFD)
1288 return;
1289
1290 /*
1291 * SocketCAN packet; fix up the packet's header.
1292 */
1293 chdr = (pcap_can_socketcan_hdr *)(buf + sizeof(struct sll_header));
1294 if (caplen < (u_int) sizeof(struct sll_header) + sizeof(chdr->can_id) ||
1295 length < (u_int) sizeof(struct sll_header) + sizeof(chdr->can_id)) {
1296 /* Not enough data to have the CAN ID */
1297 return;
1298 }
1299 chdr->can_id = SWAPLONG(chdr->can_id);
1300}
1301
1302/*
1303 * The DLT_USB_LINUX and DLT_USB_LINUX_MMAPPED headers are in host
1304 * byte order when capturing (it's supplied directly from a
1305 * memory-mapped buffer shared by the kernel).
1306 *
1307 * When reading a DLT_USB_LINUX or DLT_USB_LINUX_MMAPPED capture file,
1308 * we need to convert it from the byte order of the host that wrote
1309 * the file to this host's byte order.
1310 */
1311static void
1312swap_linux_usb_header(const struct pcap_pkthdr *hdr, u_char *buf,
1313 int header_len_64_bytes)
1314{
1315 pcap_usb_header_mmapped *uhdr = (pcap_usb_header_mmapped *)buf;
1316 bpf_u_int32 offset = 0;
1317
1318 /*
1319 * "offset" is the offset *past* the field we're swapping;
1320 * we skip the field *before* checking to make sure
1321 * the captured data length includes the entire field.
1322 */
1323
1324 /*
1325 * The URB id is a totally opaque value; do we really need to
1326 * convert it to the reading host's byte order???
1327 */
1328 offset += 8; /* skip past id */
1329 if (hdr->caplen < offset)
1330 return;
1331 uhdr->id = SWAPLL(uhdr->id);
1332
1333 offset += 4; /* skip past various 1-byte fields */
1334
1335 offset += 2; /* skip past bus_id */
1336 if (hdr->caplen < offset)
1337 return;
1338 uhdr->bus_id = SWAPSHORT(uhdr->bus_id);
1339
1340 offset += 2; /* skip past various 1-byte fields */
1341
1342 offset += 8; /* skip past ts_sec */
1343 if (hdr->caplen < offset)
1344 return;
1345 uhdr->ts_sec = SWAPLL(uhdr->ts_sec);
1346
1347 offset += 4; /* skip past ts_usec */
1348 if (hdr->caplen < offset)
1349 return;
1350 uhdr->ts_usec = SWAPLONG(uhdr->ts_usec);
1351
1352 offset += 4; /* skip past status */
1353 if (hdr->caplen < offset)
1354 return;
1355 uhdr->status = SWAPLONG(uhdr->status);
1356
1357 offset += 4; /* skip past urb_len */
1358 if (hdr->caplen < offset)
1359 return;
1360 uhdr->urb_len = SWAPLONG(uhdr->urb_len);
1361
1362 offset += 4; /* skip past data_len */
1363 if (hdr->caplen < offset)
1364 return;
1365 uhdr->data_len = SWAPLONG(uhdr->data_len);
1366
1367 if (uhdr->transfer_type == URB_ISOCHRONOUS) {
1368 offset += 4; /* skip past s.iso.error_count */
1369 if (hdr->caplen < offset)
1370 return;
1371 uhdr->s.iso.error_count = SWAPLONG(uhdr->s.iso.error_count);
1372
1373 offset += 4; /* skip past s.iso.numdesc */
1374 if (hdr->caplen < offset)
1375 return;
1376 uhdr->s.iso.numdesc = SWAPLONG(uhdr->s.iso.numdesc);
1377 } else
1378 offset += 8; /* skip USB setup header */
1379
1380 /*
1381 * With the old header, there are no isochronous descriptors
1382 * after the header.
1383 *
1384 * With the new header, the actual number of descriptors in
1385 * the header is not s.iso.numdesc, it's ndesc - only the
1386 * first N descriptors, for some value of N, are put into
1387 * the header, and ndesc is set to the actual number copied.
1388 * In addition, if s.iso.numdesc is negative, no descriptors
1389 * are captured, and ndesc is set to 0.
1390 */
1391 if (header_len_64_bytes) {
1392 /*
1393 * This is either the "version 1" header, with
1394 * 16 bytes of additional fields at the end, or
1395 * a "version 0" header from a memory-mapped
1396 * capture, with 16 bytes of zeroed-out padding
1397 * at the end. Byte swap them as if this were
1398 * a "version 1" header.
1399 */
1400 offset += 4; /* skip past interval */
1401 if (hdr->caplen < offset)
1402 return;
1403 uhdr->interval = SWAPLONG(uhdr->interval);
1404
1405 offset += 4; /* skip past start_frame */
1406 if (hdr->caplen < offset)
1407 return;
1408 uhdr->start_frame = SWAPLONG(uhdr->start_frame);
1409
1410 offset += 4; /* skip past xfer_flags */
1411 if (hdr->caplen < offset)
1412 return;
1413 uhdr->xfer_flags = SWAPLONG(uhdr->xfer_flags);
1414
1415 offset += 4; /* skip past ndesc */
1416 if (hdr->caplen < offset)
1417 return;
1418 uhdr->ndesc = SWAPLONG(uhdr->ndesc);
1419
1420 if (uhdr->transfer_type == URB_ISOCHRONOUS) {
1421 /* swap the values in struct linux_usb_isodesc */
1422 usb_isodesc *pisodesc;
1423 uint32_t i;
1424
1425 pisodesc = (usb_isodesc *)(void *)(buf+offset);
1426 for (i = 0; i < uhdr->ndesc; i++) {
1427 offset += 4; /* skip past status */
1428 if (hdr->caplen < offset)
1429 return;
1430 pisodesc->status = SWAPLONG(pisodesc->status);
1431
1432 offset += 4; /* skip past offset */
1433 if (hdr->caplen < offset)
1434 return;
1435 pisodesc->offset = SWAPLONG(pisodesc->offset);
1436
1437 offset += 4; /* skip past len */
1438 if (hdr->caplen < offset)
1439 return;
1440 pisodesc->len = SWAPLONG(pisodesc->len);
1441
1442 offset += 4; /* skip past padding */
1443
1444 pisodesc++;
1445 }
1446 }
1447 }
1448}
1449
1450/*
1451 * The DLT_NFLOG "packets" have a mixture of big-endian and host-byte-order
1452 * data. They begin with a fixed-length header with big-endian fields,
1453 * followed by a set of TLVs, where the type and length are in host
1454 * byte order but the values are either big-endian or are a raw byte
1455 * sequence that's the same regardless of the host's byte order.
1456 *
1457 * When reading a DLT_NFLOG capture file, we need to convert the type
1458 * and length values from the byte order of the host that wrote the
1459 * file to the byte order of this host.
1460 */
1461static void
1462swap_nflog_header(const struct pcap_pkthdr *hdr, u_char *buf)
1463{
1464 u_char *p = buf;
1465 nflog_hdr_t *nfhdr = (nflog_hdr_t *)buf;
1466 nflog_tlv_t *tlv;
1467 u_int caplen = hdr->caplen;
1468 u_int length = hdr->len;
1469 uint16_t size;
1470
1471 if (caplen < (u_int) sizeof(nflog_hdr_t) ||
1472 length < (u_int) sizeof(nflog_hdr_t)) {
1473 /* Not enough data to have any TLVs. */
1474 return;
1475 }
1476
1477 if (nfhdr->nflog_version != 0) {
1478 /* Unknown NFLOG version */
1479 return;
1480 }
1481
1482 length -= sizeof(nflog_hdr_t);
1483 caplen -= sizeof(nflog_hdr_t);
1484 p += sizeof(nflog_hdr_t);
1485
1486 while (caplen >= sizeof(nflog_tlv_t)) {
1487 tlv = (nflog_tlv_t *) p;
1488
1489 /* Swap the type and length. */
1490 tlv->tlv_type = SWAPSHORT(tlv->tlv_type);
1491 tlv->tlv_length = SWAPSHORT(tlv->tlv_length);
1492
1493 /* Get the length of the TLV. */
1494 size = tlv->tlv_length;
1495 if (size % 4 != 0)
1496 size += 4 - size % 4;
1497
1498 /* Is the TLV's length less than the minimum? */
1499 if (size < sizeof(nflog_tlv_t)) {
1500 /* Yes. Give up now. */
1501 return;
1502 }
1503
1504 /* Do we have enough data for the full TLV? */
1505 if (caplen < size || length < size) {
1506 /* No. */
1507 return;
1508 }
1509
1510 /* Skip over the TLV. */
1511 length -= size;
1512 caplen -= size;
1513 p += size;
1514 }
1515}
1516
1517void
1518swap_pseudo_headers(int linktype, struct pcap_pkthdr *hdr, u_char *data)
1519{
1520 /*
1521 * Convert pseudo-headers from the byte order of
1522 * the host on which the file was saved to our
1523 * byte order, as necessary.
1524 */
1525 switch (linktype) {
1526
1527 case DLT_LINUX_SLL:
1528 swap_linux_sll_header(hdr, data);
1529 break;
1530
1531 case DLT_USB_LINUX:
1532 swap_linux_usb_header(hdr, data, 0);
1533 break;
1534
1535 case DLT_USB_LINUX_MMAPPED:
1536 swap_linux_usb_header(hdr, data, 1);
1537 break;
1538
1539 case DLT_NFLOG:
1540 swap_nflog_header(hdr, data);
1541 break;
1542 }
1543}
